Bloomin’ onion! 🔥 

Super simple...

Cut your onion as seen in the video, as wide or thin as you desire, and then it’s going into a batter. 

Ingredients 👇👇👇

-2 cups of flour.
-1/2 cup of corn starch.
-1/4 to 1/2 cup of your favorite Cajun seasoning, I used @lanesbbq SPF53 . hit the link in my bio and use my code to save 15% on their products.
-add milk until you get a decent consistency, you don’t want it too thin, or too thick. (Roughly 3 cups)

Mix it all together really good and toss your onion in, making sure to spread the petals and try to get as much coverage as you can.

I fried these at 375°F for 5 minutes, making sure to flip once half way through. It’s important to cook them long enough so they will pull apart nicely.

Enjoy!

KFC Famous Bowl's. 🍗 

Slice your chicken breasts into 1-2 inch cubes and season with salt and pepper. Then hit them with some flour. Next, we're going to get our wet batter together.

Recipe:
1 cup flour
3/4 cup water 
1 egg
1 tbsp onion powder
1 tbsp garlic powder
1/2 tbsp paprika
1/2 tbsp yellow mustard
1/2 tsp canola oil 
1 tsp salt
1 tsp pepper

We're going to fry these at 350°F for 5-7 minutes until they have a nice golden color.

For the mashed potatoes, I like to keep it simple. Peel and cut a few large russet potatoes and add to a pot with a tbsp of salt and water just enough to cover the potatoes. Bring to a boil. When potatoes are fork tender, remove from heat and drain the water. Now, just add some butter and a splash of milk or heavy whipping cream to form a smooth consistency while mashing. Add salt and pepper to taste. 

Steam some yellow corn on the stove or in the microwave.

Then, make up a simple gravy of your choice. I used a store bought Turkey Gravy powder and seasoned to taste.

Enjoy!

Here’s a quick, easy version of Hoppin’ John! 🍻

What you’ll need ⬇️⬇️⬇️

-4 cups of chicken broth.
-2tbsp butter.
-18oz of shelled and pre soaked black-eyed peas. (You can buy them like this)
-1 diced white onion.
-2 diced celery stalks.
-1 diced green bell pepper.
- a handful of sliced okra.
-half a pack of cut-up bacon.
-as much diced ham as you like.
-cajun seasoning to taste.

Start by browning your bacon in a nice size pot. You’re gonna take it out and set it aside. Remove some grease, then get 2 tbsp of butter, your onions, celery, and green pepper in the pot. Once that starts to soften, add in your okra, ham, bacon, and black-eyed peas. 

In goes your broth and cajun seasoning.  Cover and simmer on low heat for a couple of hours, stirring occasionally. We served this over jasmine rice. 

I topped mine with some hot sauce and pickled jalapenos. 🔥🔥🔥

Beef Plate Ribs.. Or Dino Ribs... Whatever you call them... They are phenomenal. 🔥🔥🔥 

I rubbed these beautiful ribs from @rem5farms down with @trybachans Miso sauce as a binder. Then I hit them with a healthy dose of @lanesbbq Signature rub.

These went on the @kamadojoe pellet joe at 250F degrees for roughly 8 hours. No wrap. I sprayed them every couple of hours. I pulled them when they were probe tender and rested them in my @arcticzone cooler for 2 hours. The results were epic!

I was given this grill for an honest review. So I figured why not break it in with some beef ribs. 

Let’s start with the big stuff first, the hopper only holds 10lbs of pellets, but with it being ceramic I barely used any at all for this cook. I was surprised by that. It’s also very similar to other ceramic grills, being that it’s easy to raise the temperature, but not easy to bring it back down. I was running 250f and wanted to drop it to 225f, and it stayed at 250f. I don’t personally like how you load the pellets, it tends to get messy. also when you open the hopper door to check if it needs more, pellets come spewing out all over the ground. There isn’t a way to change out pellets, so whatever you choose, is in there until they are gone. It took a bit for temp to stabilize.. but once it did it held it perfectly. That is, until you open the grill. It tends to ramp up 50-75 degrees every time you open the grill in my experience. So leave it alone lol. The app is super simple to use and works as it should. The probes are all very accurate, which brings me to wishing they would let you set your target probe goal in 1 degree increments as opposed to the 5 degree increments that are in place. I also think it would be awesome if they could integrate using the dynamic island for us iphone users.

Overall it’s a great grill and did amazing on these ribs.

🎃 Pumpkin Pie Cheesecake with a cookie crust and whipped cream topping 🎃

This is easily my family’s favorite spooky treat this year! It’s very light and fluffy for a cheesecake and the consistency and flavor reminds me of a pumpkin pie with whipped cream. Here’s the recipe:

🍰 Ingredients/ shopping list: 
• 2 blocks of cream cheese
• 2 packages of @pillsbury Halloween sugar cookies (buy more if you want to garnish the top)
• 1 cup of Pumpkin Purée
• 1 cup of heavy whipping cream
• 3/4 cup confectioners sugar
• 1/4 cup light brown sugar
• 1 tsp vanilla extract 
• 2 tsp pumpkin pie spice
• 1/2 tsp of ground cinnamon 

👻 Homemade Whipped topping: 
• 2 cups of heavy whipping cream
• 1/4 cup of confectioners sugar (rough estimation)
• 1.5 tsp vanilla extract
Whip and set aside for later. 
OR purchase a tub of cool whip for a short cut. 

🕸️Directions: 
Spray a 9in springform pan with non stick spray. Preheat your oven to 350*F. Arrange your cookies on the bottom and bake for approx 10 mins until the cookies look slightly golden. Pull them out and set aside to cool.

Pour 1cup heavy whipping cream in your mixing bowl and blend until you get stiff peaks. Set aside.

Next, mix the room temperature cream cheese with the rest of the ingredients (pumpkin, spices, sugar) until smooth and well blended. Then gently mix or fold in the whipped cream. 

Once the cookie crust is cooled, add your pumpkin cream cheese mixture on top. Then refrigerate for at minimum 2 hours. **DO NOT add the topping yet as the cheesecake needs to cool down first and set or it will be difficult to spread over the top. Note - This cheesecake is best to be left overnight in the fridge as it will soften the cookie crust. The next day take it out and top with cool whip or homemade whipped cream and enjoy!

If you haven’t smoked your jerky before... I highly suggest it. 🔥

This is so easy, tastes way better than store bought, and way cheaper! 

Get an eye of round (any lean cut will do), and ask the butcher to cut it for you for jerky. If they won’t, you can cut it yourself using a sharp knife or grab some already cut-up Stir-fry meat. 

Pro tip: partially freeze your meat to make cutting it into thin strips a lot easier. 

Then you want to marinate your meat (18-24hrs), I used The Burn from @jerkygold, but you can use whatever you like! 

Here’s a basic jerky marinade that never fails.

👇👇👇

-2 pounds beef
-¼ cup soy sauce
-2 tablespoons worcestershire sauce
-2 tablespoons brown sugar
-2 teaspoons salt
-1 teaspoon garlic powder
-1 teaspoon onion powder
-1 teaspoon smoked paprika
-1 teaspoon black pepper

I smoked this using @bearmountainbbq cherry pellets at 180°F,  you can also use your oven and hang the strips of meat by toothpicks, making sure to have a pan or aluminum foil under them to catch the drippings. 

Keep an eye on it. The jerky is done when most of the moisture is gone from the meat. There is no set time. It usually takes a few a few hours, depending on thickness.

Ingredients 👇👇👇

-1 whole leek.
-1 pack of gourmet mushrooms.
-1 block of gruyere cheese.
-half a loaf of French bread.
-1 tbsp tarragon.
-1/4 cup of white wine.
-1 tbsp minced garlic.
-salt and pepper to taste.
-4 eggs.
-1½ cups of heavy whipping cream.
-1 cup chicken stock.
-spray oil or crisco.

Directions 👇👇👇

You’re gonna start by cubing up half a loaf of french bread and toasting it in the oven for about 10 minutes at 375°F. Then dice up your mushrooms, and slice your leek thinly, then shred your gruyere cheese. Get a tablespoon of butter in a frying pan and throw in your pancetta, followed by your leek, then your mushrooms. Add 1 tablespoon of garlic, 1 tablespoon of tarragon, and 1/4 cup of white wine of your choosing. Salt snd pepper to taste. Let this all cook together until it softens. 

In a bowl you are going to mix together 4 eggs, 1½ cups of heavy whipping cream, and 1 cup of chicken stock. Add your leek mixture to this, and then your bread. Mix it all together good and put it back in the dish you toasted your bread in. Make sure it’s greased or oiled. I put this on my pellet grill at 375°F for 30-45 minutes. This can be done in your oven as well!

Have you made your own Bacon? 👀🔥

You really should! It tastes so much better, and saves you money! 🍻

Ingredients 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼

-5lb pork belly
-1tsp prague powder #1 pink curing salt.
-5tbsp kosher salt.
-5tbsp brown sugar.
-4tbsp maple syrup.
-4tbsp coarse black pepper
-1.5 tbsp garlic powder.
-1.5 tbsp onion powder.
-1tbsp paprika.
-1tsp cayenne powder.

Mix well and rub this all over the pork belly, coating it completely.

It goes into the refrigerator vacuum sealed or in a covered dish/pan for 7 days, flipping and massaging it every day. When the 7 days are up, you’re  going to rinse it thoroughly and pat it completely dry. 

Then, put it on a wire rack uncovered in the refrigerator overnight to air dry.

This gets smoked at 200°F until it hits 150°F. (Could also be done in the oven)

Then it goes back into the fridge again overnight on a wire rack to completely cool off before slicing.

Cook it up and Enjoy! 💯
